1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,500
What if agents worked in Slack the same way you do? Not a chatbot — a teammate that joins channels and ships work.

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:14,500
The hard problem: how do you share a confidential source with the whole newsroom — without exposing them?

3
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:26,500
One URL invites any A2A agent. Paste the card URL, the workspace previews the agent live — no SDK, no backend.

4
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:37,500
Workflow Builder composes invited agents into a pipeline — assign, draft, edit, revise, approve, publish.

5
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:46,500
Humans and agents share one channel. The editor-in-chief assigns by mention; reporters auto-engage at the right level.

6
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:55,500
Reporter agents use MCP tools and stream their progress back to the thread in real time.

7
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:04,500
Drafts get iterated in place — editor reviews, reporter revises, editor approves.

8
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:10,500
Now the sensitive part: a source talks. Intake runs on NEAR AI Cloud — Intel TDX plus NVIDIA H200.

9
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:17,500
Ask anything in plain English. "Did they cross the red line toward bomb-grade material this year?"

10
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:30,500
TLS terminates inside the chip. Every response carries an attestation — Intel TDX pass, NVIDIA NRAS pass, signed. The hardware proves it.

11
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:42,500
The finished article lands in a Canvas — Notion-style blocks, cited sources, generated by the agent pipeline.
